Data Engineering with a Complex Football Database

Big Data has been revolutionary for football clubs all around the world this last decade. For example, a team of scientists specialized in data have been, in part, responsibles of the great recruitment moves from Liverpool FC that have led them to win the Premier League after 30 long years. It can guide in which player to sign, what are the most important problems in the club, performance analysis, fitness optimization...

In this project, we are going to build two models that will predict two different things: market value of players, and if a team is going to classify for some european competition. These will make use of two different datasets with also different sources.

The first model will be a Linear Regression model for predicting the market value of a player after a season considering as predictors his stats, like goals or assists. The second model will be a Generalized Linear Model for predicting whether a football team is going to classify to Champions League (UCL), Europa League (UEL) or Conference League (UECL).

1. Linear regression: predicting market values

Transfermarkt is a database of football with updated data about games, players, clubs and market valuations, with reliable and updated data about all type of stats. However, it is mainly know for its market value data as it is pretty accurate. Using this tool, we can know the value of a certain player whenever we want, without having to wait for him to be transferred to another club. We are going to use this for the first part of the project: the linear regression model. Next, we are going to explain our goals, how we are going to obtain the data and our linear regression model.

Goal: predict the market value of an attacker for LaLiga after a full season (as there is a very high number of players in the dataset, we will restrict it to attackers from LaLiga, Spanish top domestic league).

Predictors: public data available in the Transfermarkt database.

Dataset: the source code that scrapes the data from Transfermarkt is in https://github.com/dcaribou/transfermarkt-datasets, and the final datasets can be obtained through Kaggle (https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/davidcariboo/player-scores).

# Get the match_stats for LaLiga matches with a left join of appearances with games
match_stats = appearances.merge(games, on='game_id', how='left')

match_stats_laliga = match_stats[match_stats['competition_id_x'] == 'ES1']

Compose the dataset

Our desired dataset has a row per player and season, and has the values of the predictors and the market value of that season.

In[9]:
# This function creates a dataframe with one row with the player stats for a season
def player_stats(player_id, season, df):
    
    # Create a dataframe with one row for a player with player_id and season
    df = df[df['player_id'] == player_id]
    df = df[df['season'] == season]
    
    # If there is no data, returns a NaN ID and zeros
    if (df.shape[0] == 0):
        Out = [(np.nan, season,0,0,0,0,0,0,0)]
        out_df = pd.DataFrame(data = Out, columns = ['player_id','season','goals','games',
                                                     'assists','minutes_played','goals_for','goals_against','clean_sheet'])
        return out_df
    
    # If there is data, append it
    else:
        
        # These is the data for the player club, that checks if the club was at home or away for computing it
        df["goals_for"] = df.apply(lambda row: row['home_club_goals'] if row['home_club_id'] == row['player_club_id'] 
                      else row['away_club_goals'] if row['away_club_id'] == row['player_club_id'] 
                      else np.nan, axis=1)
        df["goals_against"] = df.apply(lambda row: row['away_club_goals'] if row['home_club_id'] == row['player_club_id'] 
                      else row['home_club_goals'] if row['away_club_id'] == row['player_club_id'] 
                      else np.nan, axis=1)
        df['clean_sheet'] = df.apply(lambda row: 1 if row['goals_against'] == 0
                      else 0 if row['goals_against'] > 0
                      else np.nan, axis=1)
        
        # Group by player and season, and record the data
        df = df.groupby(['player_id',"season", 'player_name'],as_index=False).agg({'goals': 'sum', 'game_id': 'nunique', 
                                                                      'assists': 'sum', 'minutes_played' : 'sum', 'goals_for' : 'sum',
                                                                      'goals_against' : 'sum', 'clean_sheet' : 'sum'})
        out_df = df.rename(columns={'game_id': 'games'})

        return out_df

We will select seasons from 2016-2017 to 2023-2024, so we have a big dataset (8 full seasons).

In[10]:
# We define the start and end season for our analisis
start_season = 2016  # Corresponds to 2016-2017
end_season = 2023

# Apply the function to all desired players and all the specified seasons
dfs = []
for season in range(start_season, end_season+1):

    for id in players['player_id']:
        
        dfs.append(player_stats(id, season, match_stats_laliga))

stats = pd.concat(dfs, ignore_index=True).dropna(subset=['player_id'])

Now, we are going to add another stat: the number of Champions League matches, as this number is probably correlated to the market value of a player (Champions League is the top clubs competition). To do it, we will use the match stats for CL matches, count the appearances for each player and add this count to our dataset.

In[19]:
# Get the count of CL matches played
match_stats_champions = match_stats[match_stats['competition_id_x'] == 'CL']
champions_counts = match_stats_champions.groupby('player_id').size().reset_index(name='cl_matches')
stats = pd.merge(stats, champions_counts, on=['player_id'], how='left')

# Some players with 0 matches have NaN, so we fill them:
stats['cl_matches'] = stats['cl_matches'].fillna(0)

We are interested in the correlations between market_value_in_eur and the rest of variables. We see that there is positive correlations for it with the following variables:

  • goals
  • games
  • assists
  • minutes_played
  • goals_for
  • clean_sheet
  • highest_market_value_in_eur
  • cl_matches

So we are going to take just this columns for the linear regression.

We have not found correlations between market value and player_id (obviously), season (seems that inflation is not a factor to consider with just 8 seasons), height, age, position and preferred foot. However, they have some reasonable and interesting correlation with other variables, like height being positive correlated to being striker and negative correlated to being winger, as strikers are usually tall and strong while wingers are usually shorter and faster.

While results are equivalent to the model without scaling, the condition number went down, so the warning was caused by the size of our variables. However, we have seen before in the heatmap that our variables were also correlated between them. In the next section, we are going to study how can we adress this.

Addressing correlation between variables

We are going to use and compare three methods for taking into account the interaction between variables:

  1. VIF: calculating the Variance Inflation Factor and dropping the predictors that have a high value.
  2. Interaction terms: creating interaction terms between our predictors.
  3. PCA: doing dimensionality reduction with Principal Components Analysis.

We will use the data without scaling as the performance is not changed and it can help us interpret better the coefficients.

VIF

From the statsmodel documentation: the variance inflation factor is a measure for the increase of the variance of the parameter estimates if an additional variable is added to the linear regression. It is a measure for multicollinearity of the design matrix.

The square root of the variance inflation factor indicates how much larger the standard error increases compared to if that variable had 0 correlation to other predictor variables in the model. Let's calculate it:

In[42]:
vif_data = pd.DataFrame()
vif_data["feature"] = lr_df[predictors].columns
vif_data["VIF"] = [variance_inflation_factor(lr_df[predictors].values, i) for i in range(lr_df[predictors].shape[1])]
print(vif_data)

Interaction terms

We are going to add interaction terms for every combination of our original predictors (except, obviously, the constant) to take into account joint effects (for example, that a goal scored for a highly valuated player adds more value than if that player is less valuated).

In[47]:
X = lr_df[predictors]
y = lr_df['market_value_in_eur']/10**6  # Market value in millions
X = sm.add_constant(X)

# Create the combinations
interactions = pd.DataFrame(index=X.index)
for (col1, col2) in combinations(X.columns[1:], 2):  # We skip the constant
    interactions[f"{col1}:{col2}"] = X[col1] * X[col2]

# Adding this interaction terms to the original predictors
X_int = pd.concat([X, interactions], axis=1)

X_train_int, X_test_int, y_train_int, y_test_int = train_test_split(X_int, y, test_size = 0.2, random_state = 1)

model_int = sm.OLS(y_train_int, X_train_int).fit()
print("\nMultiple Regression with Interactions Summary:")
print(model_int.summary())

print(f"Breusch-Pagan p-value: {bp_test[1]}")

The cone shape present in the four models means heteroscedasticity, as the variance increases as the fitted values increase. Also, the Breusch-Pagan test rejects the null hypothesis (homoscedasticity).

We have tested some ways of addressing this, as performing Weighted Least Squares or transforming our predicted variable, but performance was still similar, as we can see here:

In[59]:

As we have seen, our model has a satisfactory $R^2 \approx 0.71$ that indicates a strong fit, meaning that the predictors that we have can explain a significant proportion of our dependent variable: the market value of a player in millions of euros. Also, we have understood the meaning of the coefficients obtained, helping us understand better the relation between the variables.

Some steps could be done to improve the performance of the model. First of all, collecting more data and creating a more general model could help us understand better the market value of players with different positions, leagues or that have played in other seasons. Also, more stats could be collected, like expected goals (the goals that a player "should" have scored). Finally, it is possible that the relation that this variables follow is not completely linear. For example, we know that the best players in the world can cost up to hundreds of millions of euros, differing their market value with other players by two orders of magnitude. However, their stats do not differ by two orders of magnitude: if a striker with a value of one million score 3 goals in a season, a striker that costs 100 million cannot score 300 goals.

In the next section, we are going to apply a GLM to a different dataset. However, at the end of the project there is an extra section that applies GLMs to this market value dataset, so we can see how GLMs can improve the performance of OLS.

2. GLM

In this part of the project, we are going to predict something very different to the market value of players: the classification (or not) of a club to one os the three european football competitions: Champions League (UCL), Europa League (UEL) or Conference League (UECL).

Data preparation

The data for this part will be obtained through the website Football Reference: https://fbref.com/en/comps/Big5/Big-5-European-Leagues-Stats. It has been downloaded in the corresponding Kaggle page: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/vivovinco/20212022-football-team-stats. Also, we have created a small dataset manually that has the classifications of the different clubs for each year.

    })

    predict_data[predictor] = linspace_data

    # Predict the fitted values and confidence intervals
    predicted_values = glm_model.predict(predict_data)

    # Calculate confidence intervals (approximate with standard errors)
    se = glm_model.bse[predictor]  # Standard error for GF/MP coefficient
    ci_lower = predicted_values - 1.96 * se
    ci_upper = predicted_values + 1.96 * se

    ax = axes[i]
    ax.plot(linspace_data, predicted_values, label='Predicted Values', color='blue')
    ax.fill_between(linspace_data, ci_lower, ci_upper, color='blue', alpha=0.2, label='95% CI')
    ax.set_xlabel(predictor)
    ax.set_ylabel("Predicted Log-Odds (UCL)")

Attendance: 1372.9266758385602  16.643171297218345

We see that for every additional goal scored per match, the odds of classification are about 106.6 times higher, holding other variables constant, and for every 100,000 fans attending the match, the odds of classification are about 677.7 times higher. This shows how attendance is a huge factor to the success of the team, although we have to take into account that usually those teams with better results attract more attendance.

However, we see that for every additional goal conceded per match, the odds of classification are 0.03% as high (again, holding other variables constant). Comparing the original coefficients, we see that scoring a goal is not as important as not being scored one, roughly speaking. This shows how important defense is in football, as not receiving goals is one of the most important facts that can lead a team to the top of the classification. It is very difficult to be in the top of your league if you usually received a goal or more in each match.

The conclusion that could be extracted by manager and team directors is to focus on the defense on the team and, when this is secure, then you can start improving the attack. This is the strategy that many football managers follow, and it creates very solid teams that can classify to the top competitions.

With only three predictors, we have a good performance, with the model predicting 5 from 8 classifications, with 3 false positives. Football is a very complex sport, where the outcome depends on a lot of complex data. However, this simple model is able to do predictions about something complex as classifying to a competition.

Some possible improvements could be to take into account the differences between leagues, as countries like France usually have less places for classification than countries like England or Spain. Also, other data could be added in order to improve the performance, like the market valuation of the squad. We have seen in the first part of the project how we could do this.

Interpretation

As we can see, our model is not capable of predicting the classification for these competitions. Why?

Classification to UEL and UECL is achieve by classifying under the Champions places and over the mid table. For example, in the season 2022 of Premier League the 5th and the 6th teams classified to UEL while the 7th team classified to UECL. This means that it is very difficult to predict these places, as they have similar stats to the clubs that are near them. Also, stats like goals per match do not have a constant contribution to the outcome, as scoring more goals helps a team classify better, but this means that they have more probability of classifying to UCL, therefore not classifying to UEL or UECL.

While it is relatively easy to predict whether a team will classify to Champions, it is difficult to do it for other competitions.

EXTRA: GLM for market value

As an extra analysis of this project, we are going to combine the two parts of it. We saw that the linear regression model for predicting the market value of players was satisfactory, but linear regression with that data could not be fitted completely well. This could be due to non-linearity in the dependent variable: the market value. As we have seen that the distribution of this variable is continuous, positive and skewed:

In[107]:
sns.histplot(lr_df['market_value_in_eur'])
Out[107]:
<Axes: xlabel='market_value_in_eur', ylabel='Count'>

We can explore how a GLM would fit. For this type of data, we are going to explore three families: gamma distribution, inverse gaussian and the tweedie family, which is a distribution similar to gamma and poisson. We will compare them using the following parameters:

  • AIC (Akaike information criterion): estimator of prediction error. Lower values -> better fits.
  • Deviance: generalization of using the sum of square residuals in OLS. Lowe values -> better fits.
  • Pearson $\chi^2$: evaluates residual goodness of fit. Lower values -> better fits.
In[108]:
# Define data using the predictors from the VIF analysis
X = lr_df[new_predictors]
y = lr_df['market_value_in_eur']/10**6  # Market value in millions
X = sm.add_constant(X)

# Define our GLMs
models = {
    "Gamma (Log link)": sm.GLM(y, X, family=sm.families.Gamma(link=sm.families.links.Log())),
    "Inverse Gaussian (Log link)": sm.GLM(y, X, family=sm.families.InverseGaussian(link=sm.families.links.Log())),
    "Tweedie (Log link)": sm.GLM(y, X, family=sm.families.Tweedie(var_power=1.5, link=sm.families.links.Log())),  # var_power of 1.5 is typical for skewed continue data
}

# Fit
results = {}
for name, model in models.items():
    result = model.fit()
    results[name] = result

# Store parameters
performance = pd.DataFrame({
    "Model": list(results.keys()),
    "AIC": [res.aic for res in results.values()],
    "Deviance": [res.deviance for res in results.values()],
    "Pearson Chi2": [res.pearson_chi2 for res in results.values()]
})

print("\nPerformance Comparison:")
print(performance)

Performance Comparison:
                         Model          AIC     Deviance  Pearson Chi2
0             Gamma (Log link)  7281.303680  1133.775866    891.846888
1  Inverse Gaussian (Log link)  9766.350170   757.402512    230.246773
2           Tweedie (Log link)  7848.105435  2636.123663   2750.378593

The tweedie is clearly the worst model, as it has very high deviance and pearson $\chi^2$ and, while the inverse gaussian model has lower of these values compared with the gamma distribution, its high AIC value could indicate that it is overfitting. Because of this, we are going to investigate more the Gamma distribution model, as it is a relatively simple model but still fits well the data.

In this model, we see that the key predictors are goals, highest market value and clean sheets; while the predictors assists and cl_matches are not significant. This means that players in clubs that have more clean sheets and have had a high market value are very valuated, and this increases with the goals scored after a season.

Numerically, every additional goals scored increases the market value by approximately $e^{0.0154} -1 \approx 1.55 \%$, every additional euro in the highest market value increases the market value by $e^{3.073 \times 10^{-8}} -1 \approx 3 \times 10^{-6} \%$ and every additional clean sheet increases the market value by $e^{0.0557} -1 \approx 5.73 \%$. Taking into account that the highest market value is usually in the order of $10^6$, this shows us how important are the past highest market value (as players depend heavily on their past), clean sheets (as players in good, defensive squads are more expensive) and the goals that an attackers scores in a season. Stats like assists, for example, are not significant.

We can check the distribution of residuals:

In[112]:

We see that there is a more uniform distribution around zero compared with the residual plot of the linear regression model, meaning that probably the gamma distribution and the log link were good assumptions for our data. GLM are a great way to adress complex data predictions with simple models. However, this market value prediction probably could benefit quite a lot from more complex prediction methods that take into account the nuances of this data.
